1
00:00:16,079 --> 00:00:17,679
In northwestern Italy,

2
00:00:18,120 --> 00:00:20,399
there is a land surrounded by mountains.

3
00:00:20,920 --> 00:00:23,239
Valle d'Aosta.

4
00:00:23,239 --> 00:00:25,440
Mont Blanc, Matterhorn,

5
00:00:25,719 --> 00:00:26,879
Gran Paradiso,

6
00:00:27,559 --> 00:00:29,480
Those giants of the Alps,

7
00:00:29,879 --> 00:00:32,880
silently witnessing human insignificance and courage.

8
00:00:34,039 --> 00:00:37,320
Fifteen years ago, someone decided to do something crazy.

9
00:00:38,280 --> 00:00:40,960
to cross the giants' territory on foot.

10
00:00:41,719 --> 00:00:42,399
So,

11
00:00:42,399 --> 00:00:44,479
the Tor des Géants was born.

12
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:47,880
His name is Hai Guai.

13
00:00:48,280 --> 00:00:50,280
He lives in Beijing and loves climbing mountains.

14
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:54,000
The taller one is Bai Rui.

15
00:00:54,600 --> 00:00:55,600
He's from Northern Ireland.

16
00:00:56,240 --> 00:00:58,039
They met on Strava.

17
00:00:59,119 --> 00:01:00,719
He was also living in Beijing at the time.

18
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:03,479
After that, almost every weekend,

19
00:01:03,719 --> 00:01:05,359
they went into the mountains together.

20
00:01:07,040 --> 00:01:08,719
Until Bai Rui returned to London.

21
00:01:09,319 --> 00:01:10,799
they each got busy with their own lives,

22
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:14,120
and it became hard to meet up and climb together.

23
00:01:28,040 --> 00:01:29,120
Until one day,

24
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:31,079
Hai Guai and Bai Rui decided

25
00:01:31,519 --> 00:01:34,719
to take on the long-awaited Tor des Géants together.

26
00:01:39,040 --> 00:01:41,040
They would cross the Aosta Valley,

27
00:01:41,480 --> 00:01:43,359
covering 330 kilometers together.

28
00:01:44,040 --> 00:01:45,719
And this is where

29
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:48,280
their story begins.

30
00:02:24,719 --> 00:02:27,280
Yesterday, I did over 4,800 meters.

31
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:28,599
Of elevation gain?

32
00:02:28,599 --> 00:02:29,400
Ah.

33
00:02:29,479 --> 00:02:30,719
In forty-six kilometers.

34
00:02:30,719 --> 00:02:31,680
Ah, forty-six kilometers.

35
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:32,639
Over 4,800 meters of elevation gain.

36
00:02:33,639 --> 00:02:35,280
Hai Guai said he wasn't preparing for the race,

37
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:37,800
It was just a regular training day.

38
00:02:38,319 --> 00:02:40,560
But for most people, a daily routine like that,

39
00:02:40,919 --> 00:02:42,400
would be resume-worthy.

40
00:02:43,599 --> 00:02:44,719
Look at these two pairs of shoes.

41
00:02:46,199 --> 00:02:47,879
How many kilometers can one pair of shoes run?

42
00:02:48,719 --> 00:02:49,800
For him, running in the forest,

43
00:02:49,800 --> 00:02:50,919
to him,

44
00:02:51,159 --> 00:02:52,439
is a way of returning to nature

45
00:02:52,560 --> 00:02:53,800
and to himself.

46
00:02:54,719 --> 00:02:55,560
Every weekend,

47
00:02:55,560 --> 00:02:58,599
he heads into the mountains to recharge.

48
00:02:59,319 --> 00:03:02,159
This is where trail runners in Beijing

49
00:03:02,159 --> 00:03:03,400
do their everyday training.

50
00:03:03,520 --> 00:03:05,280
Everyone knows this place well.

51
00:03:05,800 --> 00:03:07,479
When Bai Rui and I were running in Sanfeng,

52
00:03:07,479 --> 00:03:08,719
we talked about whether

53
00:03:09,159 --> 00:03:11,240
we should sign up for a race together.

54
00:03:11,360 --> 00:03:12,560
After he moved back to London,

55
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:15,199
we knew that chances to explore the mountains together,

56
00:03:15,199 --> 00:03:17,840
would only get rarer.

57
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:20,599
A race felt like the best way to do it.

58
00:03:21,520 --> 00:03:24,800
I wanted to do a multi-day race.

59
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:26,919
That way, we could spend a lot of time together.

60
00:03:27,360 --> 00:03:28,879
If we just ran a 100K,

61
00:03:28,879 --> 00:03:29,840
or a hundred-miler,

62
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:32,719
we probably wouldn't even have time to hang out afterward.

63
00:03:32,840 --> 00:03:34,639
A multi-day race seemed much better.

64
00:03:40,639 --> 00:03:43,400
My name is Tom. I'm originally from Ireland,

65
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:44,680
but I live in London now.

66
00:03:45,240 --> 00:03:50,280
And London is a big city, far from the mountains.

67
00:03:50,319 --> 00:03:54,520
But every weekend, I get out to the local hills.

68
00:03:55,840 --> 00:03:58,120
We did a few runs together and

69
00:03:58,120 --> 00:04:01,120
quickly realized that our attitudes toward

70
00:04:01,120 --> 00:04:03,039
running and trail running were very similar,

71
00:04:03,039 --> 00:04:08,439
that we both used it as a way to explore the mountains,

72
00:04:08,439 --> 00:04:10,159
to explore the wilderness,
